{"question_id": 3699, "answer": A. Portable Operating System Interface of Linux

POSIX is a set of standards that define a set of rules and conventions that can be used to write software that can run on any Unix-like operating system, such as Linux, BSD, or Solaris. This means that software written to the POSIX standard can be compiled and run on any system that supports the standard, regardless of the underlying operating system.},
