Explanation: The system() function in Unix-like operating systems executes a command as a subprocess. It is not disabled in iOS because it is part of the C Standard Library, which is always available and does not need to be explicitly linked or included in the code. However, it should be used carefully in multi-threaded environments to avoid potential issues related to race conditions and deadlocks.},
